                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Reversing & Counting",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Sometimes you need to flip the order of a list or count how many times a value appears. Python provides simple methods for both of these tasks."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "These operations are useful for organizing data and analyzing lists."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "reverse_method",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Reversing Lists",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `reverse()` method flips the order of items in a list, putting the last item first and the first item last."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\nnumbers.reverse()\nprint(numbers)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "[5, 4, 3, 2, 1]"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The list is now in reverse order. The original list is modified."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "reverse_strings",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can reverse any type of list, including strings."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "fruits = [\"apple\", \"banana\", \"orange\"]\nfruits.reverse()\nprint(fruits)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "['orange', 'banana', 'apple']"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The list order is flipped from end to beginning."
                }
            ]
        },
