        {
            "id": "reverse_vs_sort",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Note:** `reverse()` just flips the order. It's different from `sort(reverse=True)`, which sorts from largest to smallest."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "numbers = [3, 1, 4, 2]\nnumbers.reverse()\nprint(f\"Reversed: {numbers}\")\n\nnumbers2 = [3, 1, 4, 2]\nnumbers2.sort(reverse=True)\nprint(f\"Sorted descending: {numbers2}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Reversed: [2, 4, 1, 3]\nSorted descending: [4, 3, 2, 1]"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`reverse()` flips the current order, while `sort(reverse=True)` organizes from largest to smallest."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_reverse_vs_sort",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "If you want to flip the order without sorting, which should you use?"
                },
                {
                    "type": "mcq",
                    "content": "",
                    "properties": {
                        "question": "",
                        "options": [
                            "reverse()",
                            "sort(reverse=True)",
                            "Both work the same"
                        ],
                        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
                        "correctFeedback": "Correct! reverse() just flips the order without sorting.",
                        "incorrectFeedback": "reverse() flips the order, while sort(reverse=True) sorts then reverses.",
                        "explanation": "Use reverse() to flip the order, and sort(reverse=True) to sort in descending order."
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "count_method",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Counting Items",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `count()` method tells you how many times a specific value appears in a list."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "numbers = [1, 2, 3, 2, 4, 2]\ncount = numbers.count(2)\nprint(f\"Number 2 appears {count} times\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "The number 2 appears 3 times"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`count(2)` found that the number `2` appears 3 times in the list."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "count_strings",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can count any value, including strings."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "fruits = [\"apple\", \"banana\", \"apple\"]\napple_count = fruits.count(\"apple\")\nprint(f\"Apples: {apple_count}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Apple: 2"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`count(\"apple\")` found 2 occurrences of `\"apple\"` in the list."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "count_not_found",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "If the value doesn't exist in the list, `count()` returns `0`."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "colors = [\"red\", \"green\", \"blue\"]\ncount = colors.count(\"yellow\")\nprint(count)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "0"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Since `\"yellow\"` is not in the list, `count()` returns `0`."
                }
            ]
        },
